data.title: Person: Ollie Cahill
data.meta_description: Person: Ollie Cahill: A comprehensive series of articles on this topic
data.text:
Drogheda United striker Gary O’Neill has been named the SSE Airtricity/Soccer Writers’ Association of Ireland Player of the Month for March.

ONE of the League of Ireland’s most familiar faces has decided to hang up his boots.

EOIN DOYLE came off the bench to score twice in eight minutes to keep the pressure on his former club Shamrock Rovers in the race for the title.

FORMER Bohs defender Jason McGuinness struck for the only goal of the game to book holders Sligo Rovers’ place in a third successive cup final.

Bohemians will continue their push for a European place when they take on Dundalk at Dalymount Park tonight (kick-off 7.45pm).

Derry City will be hoping to build on their impressive draw against Shamrock Rovers when they take on Bohemians at the Brandywell tonight (kick-off 7.45pm).

Bohemians will be looking to get their league challenge back on track when they take on Sligo Rovers at Dalymount Park tonight, kick-off 7.45pm.

CHAMPIONS Shamrock Rovers, two points clear at the top of the Airtricity Premier Division table and with a match in hand over second-placed Sligo Rovers, will be hoping to stretch their lead at the top when they take on UCD at the Belfield Bowl tonight (7.45).

League leaders Shamrock Rovers will be hoping to put their recent defeat to Bray behind them as they take on Bohemians at Tallaght Stadium, kick-off 8.05pm.

SHAMROCK ROVERS, two points clear at the top of the Airtricity Premier Division, bid to return to winning ways when they face Bohemians in the Dublin derby at Tallaght Stadium tonight (8.05pm, Setanta Ireland).

SHAMROCK ROVERS will be hoping to at least keep their two-point lead at the top of the Airtricity Premier Division when they take on Bray Wanderers at the Carlisle Grounds tonight (7.45).

Bohemians will be looking to stay in touch at the top of the table when they take on Dundalk at Dalymount Park tonight, kick-off 7.45pm.

SHAMROCK ROVERS can stretch their lead at the top of the Airtricity Premier Division table to six points in the Dublin derby game against fourth placed St Patrick’s Athletic at Richmond Park tonight (8.05pm — live on Setanta Ireland).

IT’S top versus second from bottom at Terryland Park this evening when Galway United host Shamrock Rovers in a televised Airtricity League Premier Division game (kick off 7.35pm, live on RTÉ 2).

Bohemians will be looking to stay in touch at the top of the table when they take on Sligo Rovers at the Showgrounds tonight, kick-off 7.35pm.

IT’S a three-way tie at the top of the Airtricity League Premier Division and, tonight, Sligo Rovers, Derry City and reigning champions Shamrock Rovers will all be seeking to break the deadlock.

Shamrock Rovers will be looking to stay top of the table when they take on Bohemians at Dalymount Park tonight, kick-off 7.35pm.

Bohemians will be looking to stay in touch at the top of the table when they take on UCD at the UCD Bowl tonight (kick-off 7.45pm).

CHAMPIONS Shamrock Rovers will be hoping to extend their lead at the top of the Airtricity Premier Division when they take on Bray Wanderers at Tallaght Stadium tonight.

PAT FENLON is still manager of Bohemians and will remain in that position over the weekend but last night’s scoreless draw with St Pat’s at Richmond Park looks increasingly likely to be his last game as Gypsies boss.

BOTTOM CLUB Galway United continued their hex on Bohemians as they recorded a valuable victory in their Airtricity League Premier Division encounter at Dalymount Park last night.

Shamrock Rovers have several injury concerns ahead of their trip to face Drogheda United at Hunky Dorys Park for tonight’s Airtricity League Premier Division clash (kick-off 7.45pm).

NEW Airtricity League-leaders Dundalk take their narrow advantage to Morton Stadium tonight for a tough assignment against third-placed Sporting Fingal (kick-off 7.45pm).

RESILIENT Cork City dealt Shamrock Rovers’ title ambitions a huge setback by coming from behind to win in Tallaght, knocking the Hoops off top spot in the Premier Division and securing their own grip on third place in the table.
